stylometry: Decision trees are important in problem solving because they organize the alternatives and possible outcomes, and also assign probability and monetary value to these decisions to determine a result. This result is based upon the highest EMV (expected monetary value). They are made up of nodes (which are the alternatives and outcomes) connected by branches which explan the probability and monetary value to the outcome and decision nodes. They are important because they provide a visual chain of possible management decisions, and also determine the best outcome. An example of how a decision tree could be used to solve a problem is going to be whether or not someone should attend their Accounting class. First we have the alternative of yes or no. We also have to detemine the probability of points lost or gained if there is homework due, a pop quiz, attendance is taken that day, or if there is an exam. Based on the probability of these outcomes and the expected monetary (in this case, point) gain or loss, decision tree will determine the best possible solution, which would probably be to attend class.
